text.tspan: 12.1.1EVALUATION AND APPROVAL OF CONTRACTORSIn order to obtain approval, a contractor is required to fill “OO 1 - HSE Questionnaire and Contractor Evaluation” which will bereviewed by the Technical Superintendent and approved by the General Manager.Amongst other factors the following shall be taken into consideration:Does the Contractor:Have safety management systems that include effective risk assessment, control of work, management of change, incidentinvestigation and environmental and emergency response systems.Have systems to provide suitable equipment that is maintained to a documented standard.Have systems to provide appropriately screened, trained, qualified and experienced personnel.Have a process for self-measurement, continuous improvement and reporting of agreed KPls to the company.Have a procedure for proactive reporting details of operational and safety performance.A list of “Approved Contractors” shall be maintained by the Technical Department.12.1.2TENDERING PROCESS AND AWARDING THE CONTRACTWhen a job / activity is to be performed which necessitates the use of Contractors the Company shall identify those contractors fromthe approved list of contractors who have the necessary capabilities to carry out the work scope.If suitable contractors are not available in the “Approved list” new contractors shall be evaluated and they shall go through theapproval process as per Section 12.1.1 above prior to being considered for use.The company shall send out a “Request for Quotation” which shall specify the scope of work to be carried out by the contractor.All eligible bids shall be evaluated and thereafter the contract shall be awarded to the most suitable contractor.12.2SCOPE OF WORK, BRIDGING DOCUMENT, KICK OFF MEETING AND ASSESSMENT ONBOARD PRIORCOMMENCEMENT12.2.1PERFORMANCE REQUIREMENTS, SCOPE OF WORK AND BRIDGING DOCUMENTThe Performance Requirements and scope of Work is to be defined clearly to contractors and subcontractors and all parties shouldmeet with the aim of understanding the work scope, responsibilities and interfaces. Performance requirements include the contractorhaving standard operating procedures that are fully consistent with those of the company and incorporate HSE expectations. Plansfor project or technical requirements are to be jointly developed with the contractor.Where difference or gaps exist, they are to be detailed in a bridging document to define roles and responsibilities for the operation andmaintenance of equipment and the applicability of HSE and management systems. This is to be prepared using the form “OO 2 -Standard Bridging Document Template” and should be in place and agreed with the Contractor prior to mobilization.12.2.2KICK OFF MEETINGA feedback mechanism is in place to ensure that the understanding of all parties, both ashore and on board, is aligned. This isachieved by holding a Kick off Meeting both ashore and onboard prior to commencement of work and is to be documented using theform “OO 3 – Minutes of Kick of Meeting”12.2.3ONBOARD ASSESSMENT AND BRIEFING OF CONTRACTORSAn onboard assessment and briefing of Contractors is to be carried prior to commencement of work in accordance with theprocedures laid down in “Vessel Operations Manual Section 3.43 – MANAGEMENT OF CONTRACTORS” to ensure that they have therequired capabilities and their staff have been properly briefed.12.2.4CONTRACTORS APPOINTED BY CLIENTS
